# Law of Demeter

**Principle of least knowledge:** a method may call only on itself, objects it creates, its parameters, and its **direct** components — not on objects returned by those calls.

**Train wreck:** chained getters used for business logic or authorization (`a.getB().getC().getD()`).

Complements [contraponto-tell-dont-ask.mdc](contraponto-tell-dont-ask.mdc): Tell avoids external state machines; Demeter avoids reaching through object graphs to read that state.

## Violations vs fixes

```java
// ❌ Train wreck — caller navigates the graph
long authorUserId = post.getBlog().getOwner().getId();
if (!comment.getPost().getAuthor().getId().equals(ownerUserId)) { … }
if (!note.getHighlight().getPost().getAuthor().getId().equals(ownerUserId)) { … }

// ✅ Entity exposes what callers need (one hop)
long authorUserId = post.getAuthorUserId();
if (!comment.getPost().isOwnedBy(ownerUserId)) { … }

// ✅ Authorization centralized in *Access
if (!postAccess.canModerate(comment.getPost(), loggedUser)) { … }
```

`Post.getAuthor()` is an acceptable **one-hop** component accessor (blog owner); still prefer `getAuthorUserId()` / `isOwnedBy(...)` when the caller only needs an id or ownership check — do not chain `.getId()` in services.

Existing `*Access` classes (`BlogAccess`, `CustomPageAccess`, `UserAccess`, `ImageAccess`) are the home for capability and ownership questions. Add `PostAccess` (or extend the nearest aggregate helper) when a new check would otherwise duplicate traversal.

## Where it applies

| Layer | Rule |
|-------|------|
| **Endpoint / Service** | No train wrecks for business rules, authorization, or event payloads. |
| **\*Access** | May use limited hops internally, but consolidate here — not spread across services. |
| **Entity** | Add `getOwnerId()`, `isOwnedBy(userId)`, `getAuthorUserId()` when multiple callers need the same hop. |
| **Repository** | JPQL/Criteria paths and `JOIN FETCH` are fine — persistence layer owns the graph. |

## Allowed chains

- **Templates / view models:** Qute may use `{post.author.username}` for display when the template already receives a loaded graph.
- **One direct component:** `post.getBlog()`, `blog.getOwner()` when that object is the value you need next (not its nested fields for decisions).
- **Repository queries:** `post.getBlog().getId()` inside a repository method building a query is acceptable.
- **Framework types:** `requestContext.getUriInfo().getPath()` — not domain logic.

## Pragmatic guidance

- **Do not** mandate a big-bang refactor of existing train wrecks.
- **Do** stop adding new chains; when touching legacy traversal, replace with an entity helper or `*Access` method in the same change (same spirit as [contraponto-no-method-bypass-allowed.mdc](contraponto-no-method-bypass-allowed.mdc)).
- Prefer **ids** over loading associations when the graph exists only for `.getId()`.
- Method names follow [domain-model.mdc](domain-model.mdc) ubiquitous language.

## Never

- Copy the same `getX().getY().getId()` ownership check into a second service — extract to `*Access` or the entity.
- Reach through aggregates in endpoints (`post.getBlog().getOwner().getUsername()` for authorization).
- Add a getter chain “because the association is already loaded” when a domain helper would keep callers stable if the model changes.
